-- ============================================================
-- RESTYLANE LYFT
-- product_id: f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506
-- FDA-indicated: cheek augmentation (2015), hand rejuvenation (2018), NLF (2004)
-- Technology: OBT (Optimal Balance Technology) — modified NASHA, 20 mg/mL HA
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'fd97029d-d32a-49c3-bfce-7043855c954e',
  'f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Restylane Lyft — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nRestylane Lyft is a stabilized hyaluronic acid dermal filler manufactured by Galderma using Optimal Balance Technology (OBT) — a modification of the NASHA (Non-Animal Stabilized Hyaluronic Acid) process that produces a firmer, higher-G'' gel than conventional Restylane. HA concentration: 20 mg/mL. Contains 0.3% lidocaine. Gel particle size: larger than standard Restylane, optimized for deep injection and volumetric correction. [FDA label Restylane Lyft PMA P020023]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nOBT cross-linking produces a cohesive gel with sufficient G'' for deep plane volumetric support (comparable to Juvederm Voluma XC in the lift indication). The OBT modification balances gel firmness with biocompatibility. HA is inherently hyaluronic acid — same molecule as native ECM HA, biodegradable by hyaluronidase. Duration of effect is extended by the cross-linking density relative to unmodified HA. [peer-reviewed: Edsman K. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol 2012]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **Cheek augmentation** to correct age-related midface volume deficit in adults ≥21 years (FDA approval 2015) [FDA label]\n- **Hand rejuvenation** to correct volume deficit in the dorsal hands in adults ≥22 years (FDA approval 2018 — first filler approved for this indication) [FDA label]\n- **Moderate-to-severe nasolabial folds** correction (FDA approval 2004, original Restylane Lyft indication) [FDA label]\n\n**Unique position:** Restylane Lyft has the broadest multi-site FDA labeling of any filler product — cheeks, hands, AND NLF. For practices offering comprehensive treatment, this breadth is clinically meaningful. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Gold M. J Drugs Dermatol 2018]\n\n**Gateway posture — off-label:** Field use extends to jawline augmentation, chin, and temples. Off-label but clinically established. [field practice]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidates:** Adults with midface volume loss, patients seeking hand rejuvenation (the "age giveaway" that patients often overlook), patients with NLF seeking longer-duration fold correction. [FDA label]\n\n**Poor candidacy signals:**\n- Active injection site infection or skin disease\n- History of anaphylaxis or allergy to gram-positive bacterial proteins (NASHA manufacture)\n- Known bleeding disorder\n- Unrealistic expectation of same-day result for hands (mild swelling may temporarily obscure correction)\n[FDA label]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Adverse events [FDA label — authority rank 1]:**\n- Common: injection site bruising, tenderness, swelling, pain, redness. Typically resolve within 2-4 weeks for face; within 1 week for hands.\n- Uncommon: inflammatory nodule, prolonged edema\n- Rare: vascular occlusion — same risk profile as all deep HA fillers; anatomy knowledge and reversal preparation required. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Broder KW. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\n**Contraindications:** Allergy to HA or gram-positive bacterial proteins; active infection at injection site. [FDA label]\n\n**Reversal:** Hyaluronidase effective. [consensus]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes Data\n\n**Cheek augmentation:** Pivotal trial. Responder rate (≥1-point MFVAS improvement at 6 months): statistically significant vs. control. Duration: up to 12 months in study data. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Moers-Carpi M. J Cosmet Dermatol 2015]\n\n**Hand rejuvenation:** FDA approval 2018. Study endpoint: improvement in Dorsal Hand Volume Scale (DHVS). Clinical data to 12 months. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Gold M. J Drugs Dermatol 2018]\n\nGateway posture: exact dosing, duration, and retreatment interval in the prescribing information [FDA/DailyMed →].',
  '02f611ad-cd03-464c-ab1a-a06bd4ead0cf',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'ad863d78-292e-4811-bb67-3e04fecac798',
  'f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Restylane Lyft — Technique Guide',
  E'## Injection Planes\n\nRestylane Lyft is a deep tissue product with three distinct indication-specific techniques:\n\n**Cheek augmentation:**\nDeep subdermal to supraperiosteal plane in the midface. Target the medial and lateral cheek fat compartments at depth to produce structural lift. Avoid superficial placement — high G'' product is palpable at surface levels. [FDA label; field practice]\n\n**Hand rejuvenation:**\nSubdermal injection on the dorsum of the hand, between the extensor tendons. Fanning or bolus technique — disperse evenly to camouflage tendon and venous prominence. 27G needle; care around visible dorsal veins. Massage post-injection to even distribution. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Gold M. J Drugs Dermatol 2018]\n\n**NLF correction:**\nMid to deep dermal plane along the fold. Linear threading or serial puncture. Depth appropriate to fold severity. [FDA label]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Exact depth (needle vs. cannula, angle, depot size) varies by anatomy and injector training. For standardized protocol, see Restylane Lyft prescribing information [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Dosing Zones (Range Characterization)\n\n- Cheeks (bilateral): approximately 2-6 mL total depending on degree of volume deficit [FDA label; field practice]\n- Hands (bilateral): approximately 1-3 mL per hand; less is typically needed for initial correction due to tissue density [FDA label]\n- NLF (bilateral): approximately 1-3 mL total [FDA label]\n\n**Gateway pointer:** For exact per-area dosing, retreatment interval, and maximum recommended volumes, see Restylane Lyft Prescribing Information [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Technique Notes\n\n- **Product handling:** OBT gel expresses similarly to Voluma XC in terms of firmness. 27G needle standard for face; 27G or 25G cannula for hands. [field practice]\n- **Hand technique pearls:** Pre-treatment photographs document vein location. Inject between tendons, not on tendon surface. Fan from single entry point medially. Immediate massage to ensure even distribution over hand dorsum. [FDA label technique guide]\n- **Cheek technique:** Bolus depots for deep supraperiosteal lift; thread/fan for volumizing the lateral subdermal layer\n\n## Treatment Planning\n\n- The multisite FDA approval makes Lyft particularly suited for a same-session face + hands combo — patients seeking comprehensive rejuvenation often request both\n- Combination with neurotoxin for brow lift, crows feet in the same session is common\n- NLF indication can be combined with cheek volumizing in a single treatment plan [field practice]\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\nFace: follow deep-to-superficial principle. Lyft for structural cheek correction first, then softer Restylane products (Refyne, Defyne) for NLF/fine lines. Same-session combination for face and hands is well-established in practice.',
  '202c5649-f39a-4cfb-a894-5913ad490b47',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '35590148-509f-4ed4-993a-4e371280eae5',
  'f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Restylane Lyft — Patient Education',
  E'## What It Does for You\n\nRestylane Lyft is the only filler FDA-approved for both cheek rejuvenation AND hand rejuvenation — which makes it uniquely positioned for patients who notice that their age shows in more than one place.\n\n**For your cheeks:** As the fat pads in the face descend over time, cheeks flatten and the midface loses its lift. Restylane Lyft was specifically engineered to restore that structural volume in the cheek region, providing a lifting and filling effect that addresses the root cause of midface aging.\n\n**For your hands:** Hands are often the overlooked area — they age visibly because the dorsal fat layer thins with age, making tendons and veins more prominent. Restylane Lyft is the first filler FDA-approved for hand rejuvenation, and it restores the soft tissue volume that makes hands look younger without changing their appearance in any way.\n\n## Why Restylane Lyft, Specifically\n\nRestylane Lyft holds more FDA-approved treatment sites than any other single filler — cheeks, hands, and nasolabial folds. This makes it a versatile, well-studied option for patients who want comprehensive treatment with a product that has been reviewed for safety in each of those locations.\n\nIt uses Galderma''s OBT technology — a stable, biocompatible HA formulation that delivers consistent results and integrates naturally with facial tissue.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During the session:** Your injector will cleanse and mark the treatment areas. For cheeks, Lyft is typically injected at deep tissue level using a fine needle. For hands, a small amount is distributed across the back of each hand using a threading or fanning technique, with gentle massage to distribute evenly.\n\n**Right after:** Immediate improvement in cheek volume or hand fullness, with some swelling and bruising. The final result in the hands settles over a week; cheeks over 2-4 weeks.\n\n**Duration:** Clinical data supports results lasting up to 12 months for cheeks and hands.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nFor cheeks: same story as any midface volumizer — structural restoration producing lift and a refreshed appearance without looking altered.\n\nFor hands: "My hands give away my age" is one of the most common statements patients make. Hand treatment is often cited as among the most satisfying: the improvement is immediate and dramatic by comparison to baseline, and people rarely expect their hands to look so much better so quickly.\n\n**Combo opportunity:** Face + hands in one session is a natural combination — patients concerned about their face often notice their hands in the same consultation. Treating both in a single appointment is efficient and addresses the full picture.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nRestylane Lyft for structure → layered with Restylane Defyne or Refyne for fold and line correction → Botox/Dysport for dynamic expression lines. A comprehensive treatment plan addresses all three layers: structure (Lyft), surface lines (Defyne/Refyne), and movement (neurotoxin).\n\n## Maintenance\n\nResults last up to 12 months in clinical studies. Maintaining the result with a touchup at 10-12 months prevents returning to baseline and typically requires less product than the initial correction.',
  'e2e32141-cf83-4475-a94d-1aafafe8d66e',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '0a549d1a-4a87-4751-90a6-268079bdd121',
  'f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Restylane Lyft — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"How is Restylane Lyft different from other Restylane products?"**\nLyft is the firmest and deepest-injecting product in the Restylane line — designed for structural volumization. Other Restylane products (Refyne, Defyne) are softer and used for fold correction and fine lines. Lyft is the foundation product.\n\n**"I hadn''t thought about treating my hands — do people actually do that?"**\nHand rejuvenation is one of the fastest-growing filler indications. Restylane Lyft is the first filler FDA-approved specifically for hands. The result — restoring the soft tissue volume that makes tendons and veins less prominent — can be remarkable and patients frequently report it as among their most satisfying aesthetic treatments.\n\n**"Will my hands look natural after treatment?"**\nYes. The goal is not to change the shape of your hands, just to restore the fullness they had before age-related volume loss. The result reads as "healthy, youthful-looking hands" — not treated.\n\n**"Can I do my face and hands in the same appointment?"**\nAbsolutely — this is a common combination. Many patients find it efficient to address both in one session.\n\n**"What if I don''t like the result?"**\nLike all HA fillers, Restylane Lyft can be dissolved with hyaluronidase. Reversal is effective, though not instant.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I''m not sure I want to treat my hands."**\nHands are often what patients notice most when they look at photos but can''t quite explain why they look "older." Once patients understand that the aging process depletes the same fat layer in hands as in the face, they often see the connection. Most patients who treat their hands report being glad they did.\n\n**"Is this safe on my hands?"**\nFDA reviewed safety data specifically for dorsal hand injection before approving Restylane Lyft for this use. The safety profile for hand treatment is well-established, and the technique (avoiding major vessels) is well-understood by trained injectors.',
  'e2e32141-cf83-4475-a94d-1aafafe8d66e',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '2a9819ae-4790-4707-9263-19f61e871240',
  'f1732c7c-3f19-4f3d-9aff-543a132e5506',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Restylane Lyft — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\nRestylane Lyft''s unique competitive position: it is the only FDA-approved filler for dorsal hand rejuvenation — a fact that matters in practices where patients present with hand concerns alongside facial concerns. No other single filler has the tripartite FDA approval (cheeks + hands + NLF).\n\nVersus Juvederm Voluma XC in the cheek indication: both have FDA cheek augmentation approval, comparable G'' and duration, and strong safety records. Key differences: Voluma uses Vycross (higher cohesivity); Lyft uses OBT (modified NASHA). Clinical preference varies by injector training and familiarity. No published head-to-head RCT directly comparing cheek outcomes. The product choice in this indication often comes down to practice preference and patient anatomy.\n\nVersus conventional Restylane for NLF: Lyft is firmer and appropriate for deep NLF; standard Restylane is for moderate NLF at shallower depth. Selection should match fold depth to product rheology.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**OBT (Optimal Balance Technology):** A modified NASHA process. The NASHA base uses bacterial fermentation of HA followed by BDDE cross-linking. OBT modifies the process to produce a larger gel particle with higher cross-link density — resulting in higher G'' and longer duration compared to standard NASHA Restylane, while retaining the safety profile of the established NASHA platform. [peer-reviewed: Edsman K. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol 2012]\n\nWhy this matters clinically: NASHA technology has 20+ years of global safety data. OBT builds on that established platform rather than introducing a fundamentally different chemistry (as Vycross does). For practices that value long-established HA safety documentation, NASHA-lineage products have the most extensive clinical record.\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**Cheek augmentation pivotal study:** Responder analysis per MFVAS. [FDA label PMA P020023 supplement]\n\n**Hand rejuvenation study:** Evaluator-blinded, controlled. Primary endpoint: DHVS improvement at 6 months. First FDA-approved filler for this indication (2018). [FDA label; Gold M. J Drugs Dermatol 2018]\n\n**Key publications:**\n- Edsman K et al. J Eur Acad Dermatol Venereol 2012 — OBT/NASHA physicochemical characterization\n- Gold M et al. J Drugs Dermatol 2018 — Hand rejuvenation pivotal data, patient-reported outcomes\n- Moers-Carpi M et al. J Cosmet Dermatol 2015 — Cheek augmentation comparative outcomes\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Parameter | Restylane Lyft | Juvederm Voluma XC | Restylane Defyne |\n|-----------|---------------|---------------------|------------------|\n| G'' | High (OBT) | High (Vycross ~800 Pa) | Medium (OBT) |\n| Key FDA indication | Cheeks, hands, NLF | Cheeks, chin | NLF, marionette |\n| Duration | ~12 months | ~18-24 months | ~12 months |\n| Technology | OBT (NASHA mod) | Vycross | OBT (NASHA mod) |\n| Hand indication | YES (FDA) | No FDA | No FDA |\n\nGateway posture: rheological values and duration from published literature and FDA submissions; individual patient outcomes vary. For exact parameters, refer to prescribing information.',
  '8044bea2-d637-4251-89e4-0f420699eab0',
  'draft', 1
);

-- ============================================================
-- RHA REDENSITY (RHA Collection — Teoxane)
-- product_id: d8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930
-- FDA-cleared: perioral lines (2020) — first RHA product FDA-approved in US
-- Technology: Resilient Hyaluronic Acid (RHA) — preserved HA chain length, fewer cross-links
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'a12eb1ab-7ed8-490f-8464-8329eabea4b8',
  'd8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'RHA Redensity — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nRHA Redensity is part of the RHA Collection (Resilient Hyaluronic Acid), manufactured by Teoxane SA and distributed by Revance Aesthetics. It is the most superficial-plane product in the RHA line, specifically designed for perioral lines (dynamic and static). FDA clearance 2020 for perioral rhytids. HA concentration: 15 mg/mL. Contains lidocaine. [FDA label RHA Redensity K183782]\n\nDistinctive technology: **Resilient HA (RHA)** — preserves the native HA polymer chain length more than conventional cross-linking methods, using a gentle cross-linking process that maintains the viscoelastic flexibility similar to native dermal HA. The result is a filler that stretches and recovers with facial movement rather than fracturing or displacing. [peer-reviewed: Micheels P. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2021]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nConventional cross-linked HA fillers (NASHA, Vycross) sacrifice chain integrity for gel firmness — the cross-links create structure but reduce the inherent chain flexibility of native HA. RHA technology preserves longer HA polymer chains while using fewer cross-links, producing a gel with viscoelastic properties closer to native ECM HA. This means the product deforms elastically under tensile load (facial movement, expression) and recovers to shape — rather than fracturing or displacing. [peer-reviewed: Jegasothy S. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2020]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Indications\n\n- **Perioral rhytids (perioral lines)** in adults ≥22 years (FDA clearance 2020) [FDA label K183782]\n\n**Gateway posture — other RHA products in the collection (not Redensity):** RHA 2, 3, and 4 are FDA-cleared for dynamic wrinkles at different depths and volumes. RHA Redensity specifically targets the perioral superficial zone. [FDA labels]\n\n**Off-label field use:** RHA Redensity is used for tear trough, under-eye hollows, and fine superficial lines throughout the face. These are off-label but leverage the product''s native-feel integration. [field practice]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidates:**\n- Patients with perioral lines (lipstick lines, smoker''s lines) that worsen with dynamic pursing — RHA''s flexibility means it moves with the lip rather than fragmenting with pursing\n- Patients who have had conventional filler in the perioral area that looked lumpy or felt stiff with movement\n- Patients seeking a more "natural feeling" filler experience\n[FDA label; peer-reviewed: Jegasothy S. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2020]\n\n**Poor candidacy signals:**\n- Patients needing volumetric correction (RHA Redensity is not a volumizer)\n- Active perioral infection (herpes simplex — prophylaxis for high-risk patients should be considered)\n- Allergy to HA or lidocaine [FDA label]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Adverse events [FDA label — authority rank 1]:**\n- Common: injection site swelling, bruising, tenderness, discoloration, papules. Typically resolve within 2-3 weeks.\n- Uncommon: prolonged edema\n- Rare: vascular occlusion — risk in perioral region (labial arteries) is present; anatomy knowledge required [FDA label]\n\n**Contraindications:** Allergy to HA or lidocaine; active infection at injection site. [FDA label]\n\n**Reversal:** Hyaluronidase effective. [consensus]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes Data\n\n**FDA clearance study (K183782):** Evaluator-blinded, controlled. Primary endpoint: improvement in perioral rhytid severity. Statistically significant improvement vs. control at primary timepoint. [FDA label]\n\n**Key differentiating data point:** Multiple published assessments report that RHA products, including Redensity, produce a result that patients and blinded evaluators describe as more "natural-looking" and "natural-feeling" in dynamic zones compared to conventional fillers — attributed to the RHA elastic recovery behavior. [peer-reviewed: Micheels P. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2021]\n\nGateway posture: individual outcomes vary with anatomy, volume placed, and skin quality. Duration data and retreatment interval in prescribing information [FDA/DailyMed →].',
  '02f611ad-cd03-464c-ab1a-a06bd4ead0cf',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'b41c72a5-3343-4803-b001-60b82cf9310b',
  'd8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'RHA Redensity — Technique Guide',
  E'## Injection Planes\n\nRHA Redensity is a superficial plane product:\n\n- **Perioral lines:** Superficial to mid-dermis. Retrograde threading along individual lip lines. Very small volume per thread (0.02-0.05 mL per line). Serial puncture acceptable but threading produces more even distribution. [FDA label; consensus]\n- **Under-eye/tear trough (off-label):** Very superficial or intradermal. The elastic recovery of RHA is particularly suited for this highly mobile area. Extreme care required — thin skin, venous anatomy. [field practice — off-label]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Perioral technique details (needle gauge, depth, volume per pass) are procedure-specific; sources describe both needle and cannula approaches. For standardized protocol, see RHA Redensity instructions for use [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Dosing Zones (Range Characterization)\n\n- Perioral lines (full treatment): typically 0.5-1.5 mL per session\n- Individual lip line: 0.02-0.1 mL per line depending on depth\n- Under-eye (off-label): fractions of 0.1-0.3 mL per side\n\n**Gateway pointer:** Exact volumes from clinical trial protocol in prescribing information [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Technique Notes\n\n- **Retrograde threading:** Gold standard for lip line correction — moves product parallel to the line, avoiding bolus buildup\n- **Needle gauge:** 30G-32G preferred for the superficial plane — smaller needle reduces bruising in this highly vascular zone\n- **Herpes simplex prophylaxis:** For patients with prior perioral HSV, consider prophylactic antiviral before treatment [field practice consensus]\n- **RHA elasticity:** The product may feel less firm than conventional fillers on palpation — this is expected and appropriate; it is the "soft" end of the RHA range\n- **Lumps:** If small papules form, gentle massage post-injection. Product''s elastic recovery means it distributes well with kneading.\n\n## Treatment Planning\n\n- RHA Redensity is frequently the final step in a perioral sequence: Botox/Dysport for orbicularis function modulation → Vollure XC or Defyne for deeper NLF → RHA Redensity for fine superficial lip lines\n- For patients with a history of "stiff lip" after conventional perioral filler, RHA Redensity''s elastic properties address this complaint directly\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\nPerioral sequence (common practice): structural NLF correction (Vollure/Defyne) → perioral line fine-tuning (RHA Redensity) → lip definition if needed (Kysse or Volbella XC). Neurotoxin for dynamic component as a separate consideration. RHA Redensity should be injected last in a layered approach.',
  '202c5649-f39a-4cfb-a894-5913ad490b47',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '9a989a2e-a99a-400d-abdd-062182667d89',
  'd8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'RHA Redensity — Patient Education',
  E'## What It Does for You\n\nRHA Redensity is a uniquely engineered filler designed specifically for the delicate area around your lips — the fine lines that form there over time. What makes RHA different is its technology: instead of a conventional firm gel that stays rigid while your face moves, RHA Redensity stretches and recovers with your facial expressions — so the result moves naturally with you.\n\nPerioral lines (the vertical lines above and below the lip border, sometimes called "lipstick lines" or "smoker''s lines") are notoriously difficult to treat because the perioral area is in constant motion — talking, smiling, kissing. Conventional fillers sometimes look lumpy, feel stiff, or create a "duck lip" effect in this zone because they don''t adapt to movement. RHA Redensity was specifically designed to solve this problem.\n\n## Why RHA Redensity, Specifically\n\nThe HA in RHA products is processed to preserve its natural chain structure more than conventional cross-linking methods — the result is a filler that behaves more like native skin HA. Patients and independent evaluators consistently describe RHA results in dynamic zones as looking and feeling more natural than conventional filler in the same area.\n\nRHA Redensity is FDA-cleared specifically for perioral lines — it is a purpose-built, studied product for this indication, not an off-label use of a product designed for something else.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During the session:** Very fine needle injection along each lip line. The perioral area is sensitive — the lidocaine in the product provides comfort, and your injector may use topical numbing as well.\n\n**Right after:** Some bruising is common in this zone (the perioral area is vascular). Swelling typically resolves within a week.\n\n**Duration:** Clinical data supports perioral line improvement at 6-12 months; individual variation exists.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nLip lines are often what patients describe as making them "look older." They cause lipstick to bleed and make the lip border look less defined. Treating lip lines with a product engineered for the movement of this area provides a smooth, natural result that enhances the entire lower face — without the "frozen" or "filler face" appearance that poorly matched products can create.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nRHA Redensity addresses fine perioral lines — the surface layer. For a complete perioral result:\n- Juvederm Vollure XC or Restylane Defyne corrects the deeper NLF and fold\n- Botox/Dysport modulates the orbicularis muscle''s dynamic pursing component\n- RHA Redensity adds the fine-line finishing layer\n\nThis three-layer approach (fold, muscle, fine line) is how comprehensive perioral rejuvenation is typically structured.\n\n## Maintenance\n\nRHA Redensity''s duration in the perioral zone is typically 6-12 months. Many patients incorporate it into a twice-yearly maintenance plan — combining it with their neurotoxin appointments.',
  'e2e32141-cf83-4475-a94d-1aafafe8d66e',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '544a9644-60a5-4aa6-b523-3ac391729110',
  'd8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'RHA Redensity — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"I had filler in my lip lines before and it looked lumpy. Will this be different?"**\nThe most common cause of lumps around the lip is a product that is too firm for the superficial perioral plane — conventional high-G'' fillers can collect and feel rigid in thin tissue. RHA Redensity is specifically designed with elastic recovery for this area. It integrates with movement rather than resisting it, which dramatically reduces the lumpy/stiff outcome some patients have experienced with other products.\n\n**"Will it look natural when I smile and talk?"**\nThis is exactly what RHA was designed for. The product''s elastic properties mean it moves with your face rather than staying rigid. Clinical evaluations consistently report that RHA results in dynamic zones look and feel more natural than conventional filler.\n\n**"How does it compare to Botox for lip lines?"**\nThey address different components of the same problem. Botox can reduce the pursing muscle action that creates dynamic lip lines. RHA Redensity fills the static lines that remain at rest. Many patients benefit from both for a complete result — neurotoxin for the muscle component, filler for the static line depth.\n\n**"Will there be bruising?"**\nBruising is common in the perioral region because it is highly vascular. Your injector will take precautions, but prepare for possible 7-10 days of bruising. Arnica and avoiding blood thinners before treatment can help reduce bruising.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I''m afraid filler around my lips will look overdone."**\nRHA Redensity is not a lip volumizer — it treats the fine lines around the lip border, not the lips themselves. The result is a smoother lip border and a reduction in the lines that cause lipstick to bleed. You won''t look fuller; you''ll look smoother. If lip volume is also a goal, that is a separate discussion about a different product.\n\n**"I don''t want to commit to regular filler."**\nPerioral lines are typically treated once or twice a year at most. RHA Redensity''s natural feel and appropriate durability mean you are not committing to monthly appointments — it is a maintenance treatment that fits into a normal annual or semi-annual aesthetic rhythm.',
  'e2e32141-cf83-4475-a94d-1aafafe8d66e',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
