  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'ef6b56b6-5dcf-4583-804b-d28ea8ec1e24',
  'd8a00419-39e1-4d4b-8dab-ad134fb00930',
  '138ed383-364a-44a3-87a0-8e641ecd4200',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'RHA Redensity — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\nRHA Redensity occupies a unique niche: the only FDA-cleared filler specifically for perioral rhytids with RHA (elastic recovery) technology. Its differentiation is not primarily about duration or lift capacity — it is about material behavior in dynamic zones. The elastic recovery property directly addresses the most common patient complaint about conventional perioral filler (lumpiness, stiffness, unnatural feel with movement).\n\nWithin the RHA Collection: Redensity is the finest/most superficial product. RHA 2, 3, and 4 address progressively deeper and higher-volume dynamic wrinkle indications. Redensity is specifically the perioral fine-line product.\n\nVersus Volbella XC (Allergan) in perioral indication: Both are fine-plane, low-G'' perioral products. Volbella uses Vycross with lower cohesivity; Redensity uses RHA elastic cross-linking. Both are FDA-cleared for perioral/lip indication. Practitioner preference and patient anatomy drive selection — no head-to-head comparative RCT. [field practice — sources differ]\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**RHA (Resilient Hyaluronic Acid) technology:** Teoxane''s proprietary modification of HA cross-linking. Standard BDDE cross-linking fragments HA polymer chains at cross-link points — producing a gel with reduced chain length and lower inherent flexibility. RHA uses a gentler process that:\n1. Preserves longer native HA polymer chains\n2. Uses fewer cross-links per unit volume\n3. Results in viscoelastic behavior (elastic recovery) rather than purely plastic deformation\n\nMeasured outcome: RHA gels show elastic recovery after compression/extension — they return to shape. Conventional HA fillers show more plastic deformation (permanent shape change under stress). This is measurable in rheology and clinically observable as the product moving naturally with expression vs. staying rigid. [peer-reviewed: Micheels P. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2021]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**FDA clearance (K183782, 2020):** Pivotal study for perioral rhytids. Evaluator-blinded, controlled. Significant improvement in perioral rhytid severity vs. control. First RHA product to receive US FDA clearance. [FDA label]\n\n**Key publications:**\n- Micheels P et al. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2021 — RHA technology review, mechanism, and clinical outcomes\n- Jegasothy S et al. J Clin Aesthet Dermatol 2020 — Clinical evaluation of RHA Collection in dynamic wrinkles\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Parameter | RHA Redensity | Volbella XC | Vollure XC |\n|-----------|--------------|-------------|------------|\n| Technology | RHA (elastic recovery) | Vycross (low G'') | Vycross (med G'') |\n| Primary indication | Perioral lines | Lip + perioral | NLF + perioral |\n| Plane | Superficial dermis | Superficial to mid | Mid dermis |\n| Dynamic behavior | Elastic recovery | Semi-rigid | Semi-rigid |\n| FDA clearance | Perioral rhytids | Lip/perioral | NLF/perioral |\n\nGateway posture: rheological characterization from published literature; clinical outcomes vary with technique and patient anatomy. For exact specifications, see prescribing information.',
  '8044bea2-d637-4251-89e4-0f420699eab0',
  'draft', 1
);
